  "texts": [
    "They leverage high-bandwidth, wired or persistent network connections to process large-scale language models, access remote knowledge bases, and interact with users via graphical, voice, or wearable interfaces.",
    "• Embodied agents, such as home robots, UAVs, and autonomous vehicles, inhabit the physical world and rely on onboard sensors (e.g., cameras, LiDAR, inertial measurement units) and actuators to perceive and manipulate their environment [4].",
    "They generally operate under variable wireless conditions for remote coordination.",
    "2) Functional Modules of Agents.",
    "Regardless of form, as depicted in Fig. 2, each IoA agent typically comprises four core functional modules [1], [2]: planning, memory, interaction, and action, which together empower agents to operate, learn, and adapt in complex environments.TABLE III COMPARISON AMONG SYMBOLIC AGENTS, LLM-POWERED VIRTUAL AGENTS, AND ROBOTIC/EMBODIED AGENTS Agent Type Core Mechanism Strengths Limitations Roles in IoA Symbolic Agents Logic-based or rule-driven inference and decision-making High interpretability, formal guarantees, efficient in structured domains Limited scalability, less flexible in unstructured environments Protocol enforcement, rule-based coordination, compliance checking LLM-powered Virtual Agents Generative large models for reasoning, planning, and natural language interaction Strong adaptability, contextual reasoning, multi-domain capability Computationally expensive, unpredictable behavior, reliance on data quality Conversational agents, code generation, research assistants Robotic/Embodied Agents Coupling perception with actuation in the physical world Direct real-world interaction, physical task execution Hardware constraints, safety/reliability concerns, limited reasoning ability Manufacturing, autonomous vehicles, healthcare robotics Tools External knowledge Feedback Environment (Human/Cyber/Physical Worlds) Observation Action Memory Interaction Planning Strategy Virtual/Embodied Agent Brain (Large Model) Body (Sensor & Actuator)Fig."
  ]
